            <section class="mt-10 prose">
              <h2>How this coffee cost calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool focuses on what matters to most coffee drinkers:
                <strong>cost per cup</strong>,
                <strong>monthly and yearly spending</strong>, and the
                <strong>savings from brewing at home vs buying at a café</strong
                >. Unlike commodity price charts that show futures contracts or
                wholesale prices, this calculator uses the numbers you actually
                see in the supermarket or at your local coffee shop.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Cost per cup formulas</h3>
              <p>
                For beans, ground coffee and instant coffee we work in grams so
                results are consistent across package sizes.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Normalize package size to grams</strong></p>
                <p>
                  If your bag or jar is not already in grams, we convert it:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>1 kg = 1000 g</li>
                  <li>1 lb ≈ 453.592 g</li>
                  <li>1 oz ≈ 28.3495 g</li>
                </ul>
                <p><code>package_grams = weight × conversion_factor</code></p>
                <hr class="my-3" />
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Cups per package</strong></p>
                <p>
                  <code>cups_per_package = package_grams ÷ grams_per_cup</code>
                </p>
                <hr class="my-3" />
                <p><strong>Step 3 – Cost per cup (coffee only)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  <code>cost_per_cup = package_price ÷ cups_per_package</code>
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                For pods and capsules we simply divide the box price by the
                number of pods:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Pods / capsules</strong></p>
                <p><code>cost_per_cup = box_price ÷ pods_per_box</code></p>
              </div>

              <p>
                For café drinks you usually know the price per drink already, so
                the cost per cup is just that price.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Including equipment cost</h3>
              <p>
                If you choose to include equipment (machine, grinder, kettle,
                etc.), we amortize it over its expected lifetime and add it to
                each cup.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Equipment cost per month</strong></p>
                <p><code>months_of_use = years_of_use × 12</code></p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >equip_cost_per_month = total_equip_cost ÷
                    months_of_use</code
                  >
                </p>
                <hr class="my-3" />
                <p><strong>Home cups per month</strong></p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >home_cups_per_month = cups_per_day × days_per_week × (52 ÷
                    12)</code
                  >
                </p>
                <hr class="my-3" />
                <p><strong>Equipment cost per cup</strong></p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >equip_cost_per_cup = equip_cost_per_month ÷
                    home_cups_per_month</code
                  >
                </p>
                <hr class="my-3" />
                <p><strong>Total cost per cup (with equipment)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >total_cost_per_cup = coffee_cost_per_cup +
                    equip_cost_per_cup</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Monthly and yearly coffee spending</h3>
              <p>
                Once we know cost per cup and how many cups you drink per day,
                we estimate your budget:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Daily cups</strong>: <code>cups_per_day</code></p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Monthly cups</strong>:
                  <code>cups_per_month ≈ cups_per_day × 30.4</code>
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Yearly cups</strong>:
                  <code>cups_per_year ≈ cups_per_day × 365</code>
                </p>
                <hr class="my-3" />
                <p>
                  <strong>Monthly cost</strong>:
                  <code>monthly_cost = cost_per_cup × cups_per_month</code>
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Yearly cost</strong>:
                  <code>yearly_cost = cost_per_cup × cups_per_year</code>
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Comparing home vs café coffee</h3>
              <p>
                To show how much you could save by brewing at home, we compare
                your home cost per cup with a café price per drink:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Difference per cup</strong></p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >delta_per_cup = cafe_price_per_drink −
                    home_cost_per_cup</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  If <code>delta_per_cup &gt; 0</code>, home is cheaper by that
                  amount per cup.
                </p>
                <hr class="my-3" />
                <p><strong>Yearly savings</strong></p>
                <p>
                  <code>yearly_savings = delta_per_cup × cups_per_year</code>
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Practical examples</h2>

              <h3>Example 1 – Whole beans vs café latte</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Bag price: $12</li>
                <li>Bag weight: 340 g</li>
                <li>Dose per cup: 17 g</li>
                <li>Cups per day: 2</li>
                <li>Café price per drink: $4.50</li>
              </ul>
              <p>From the formulas:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Cups per bag ≈ 340 ÷ 17 ≈ 20 cups</li>
                <li>Cost per cup (beans only) ≈ $12 ÷ 20 = $0.60</li>
                <li>Monthly cups ≈ 2 × 30.4 ≈ 61 cups</li>
                <li>Monthly home cost ≈ 61 × $0.60 ≈ $36.60</li>
                <li>Monthly café cost ≈ 61 × $4.50 ≈ $274.50</li>
                <li>Yearly savings ≈ ($4.50 − $0.60) × (2 × 365) ≈ $2,847</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Example 2 – Pods vs beans</h3>
              <p>Suppose:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Pods: $18 for 40 pods → $0.45 per cup</li>
                <li>Beans: $12 for 340 g, 17 g per cup → $0.60 per cup</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In this case pods are actually cheaper per cup than your chosen
                beans. However, if you buy beans in larger bags or at lower
                prices, beans often win. The calculator lets you quickly test
                different scenarios.
              </p>

              <h2>
                Tips to reduce your coffee cost without sacrificing quality
              </h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Buy larger bags</strong> – per-gram prices usually
                  drop with 1 kg bags vs 250–340 g bags.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Dial in your dose</strong> – many people use more
                  coffee than needed; try small reductions and taste the
                  difference.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use a scale</strong> – consistent dosing avoids waste
                  and improves flavor.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider equipment lifespan</strong> – a good grinder
                  or machine can pay for itself quickly if you drink coffee
                  daily.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Track your real consumption</strong> – adjust “cups
                  per day” to match weekdays vs weekends for more accurate
                  budgeting.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="mt-10 prose">
              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How do you calculate the cost per cup of coffee?</h3>
              <p>
                We divide the total cost of the package (bag, box or jar) by the
                number of cups it can make. For beans and instant coffee we
                convert the package to grams, divide by grams per cup to get
                cups per package, then divide price by cups. For pods we divide
                box price by pod count. For café drinks we use the price per
                drink directly.
              </p>

              <h3>Is it cheaper to make coffee at home or buy it at a café?</h3>
              <p>
                For regular coffee drinkers, home brewing is almost always
                cheaper. A typical home cup costs $0.30–$0.70, while café drinks
                are often $3–$6. Even after including equipment cost, daily café
                visits usually cost hundreds or thousands more per year than
                home brewing.
              </p>

              <h3>How many cups are in a bag of coffee?</h3>
              <p>
                It depends on bag size and your dose per cup. With a common
                recipe of 15–18 g per 250 ml cup, a 340 g (12 oz) bag yields
                roughly 19–23 cups. The calculator shows cups per bag as soon as
                you enter bag weight and grams per cup.
              </p>

              <h3>What dose per cup should I use?</h3>
              <p>
                Many specialty coffee recipes use 1:15–1:17 coffee-to-water
                ratios by weight. For a 250 ml cup that’s about 15–17 g of
                coffee. If your coffee tastes weak, increase the dose slightly;
                if it’s too strong or bitter, decrease it. The calculator works
                with any dose you choose.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I include milk, sugar and other add-ons?</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on the coffee itself and optional
                equipment. If you want a full drink cost, you can estimate the
                extra cost of milk, syrups and sugar per cup and add it manually
                to the cost per cup shown in the results.
              </p>
            </section>
